Q. I am interested in your gun. Is it still available?

If someone has made it just before you, I will notify you within a short time (usually, an hour), otherwise - see you shortly.

PLEASE DO NOT ASK WHETHER THE GUN IS STILL AVAILABLE! I WILL NOT RESPOND.

Q. How do I buy?
A. This is a dealer listing, NICS check, taxes, etc are all required. Please go to www.preciseshooter.com -> FAQ -> How to buy, read the requirements, and make the appointment to pick up.

Q. I am interested in your gun. Call me @ xxx-xxx-xxxx
A. Excellent. Go to www.preciseshooter.com -> FAQ -> How to buy, read the requirements, and make the appointment to pick it up.

Q. Are there any other fees, in addition to the price and taxes? NICS, background check, etc?
A. No.

Q. What is the tax rate?
A. 9.5%

Q. Where are you located?
A. Queen Anne neighborhood in Seattle.

Q. Can we meet in Burien on Monday morning?
A. No, FFL requirements are that the transfers happen at a licensed location. Also, the only times you can come over are the appointments that you can reserve on the site. No other time slots are available.

Q. I see you carry Savage rifles. Can you find me MKII FV-SR?
A. No. Please see here for what I can or cannot do: http://www.preciseshooter.com/NotInStock.aspx

Q. Do you take trades?
A. Sometimes. However:
a) firearms only,
b) they need to be our of current production (I can get new ones at wholesale prices), or you have to offer them to me at well below wholesale
c) I do not resell the trades, so they should fit my personal interests (which only include military as well as highly accurate, competition guns - no self defense guns like Glocks, M&Ps, XD*, and the like)
d) the exchange rate should be fair (see here for more: http://www.preciseshooter.com/blog/PriceGuide.aspx

Q. Is the price firm? Will you take XXX (70% of the asking price)?
A. The price is firm.

Q. Can you help me mount a scope/replace a trigger/fix a feeding problem?
A. Sorry, I do not do gunsmithing.

Q. Will you ship?
A. Yes - go to www.preciseshooter.com -> How to buy and read the section for buying outside Seattle area. Insured shipping for this pistol will be $20.

The TAVOR® is supplied with IDF-tested and approved magazines – but you can also use your own AR-15/M16 style magazines. title: For Sale:  Kel-Tec PF-9, 9mm Luger
postcontent:
This is the newer rendition of the PF-9. Includes three 7-round factory magazines and a pocket holster. The gun comes from the factory with one magazine and extras cost about $22. The holster is valued at about $10 and has only been used to protect the gun in storage. 

All included with the pistol:
3 7-rounnd factory magazines
1 pocket holster
1 trigger lock
1 extra magazine base pad with finger rest
1 extra Kel-Tec factory replacement extractor (new and unused)
1 extra Kel-Tec factory replacement extractor leaf spring (new and unused)
1 extra Kel-Tec factory replacement extractor screw (new and unused)
Owners manual
Factory original hard case

PLEASE READ ABOUT THIS GUN'S HISTORY BELOW. After owning this pistol, I cannot honestly recommend anyone buying anything with the Kel-Tec name on it, but if you want to try your luck with this, have at it.

This pistol cycles reliably with brass cased ammunition. Aluminum cases (such as CCI Blazer) have occasional failures to extract. Some European ammunition with hard primers (Sellier & Bellot, Herters Brass) do not ignite reliably. Standard pressure American made factory loads work just fine. I have not used steel cased ammunition in this pistol and would not recommend doing so.

The slide has been replaced by Kel-Tec. The original developed a hairline crack after only 400 rounds--factory, standard pressure only. Replacing the slide means the gun also has a new firing pin, extractor, and related hardware. The new slide assembly has only seen about 20 rounds.

Be sure to keep the screw on the extractor spring tight. I put some blue thread-lock on this one. If the screw loosens, the firing pin will spring out of the back of the slide. I lost the first one prior to the slide replacement. 

The assembly pin has also been replaced twice by the manufacturer after it sheared in half. As noted above, I have only used standard pressure, factory 9mm Luger ammunition in this gun. 

Everything broken has been replaced with new parts. The gun has been cleaned and maintained properly. It has spent most of its existence in the safe.

Buyer must show a Wisconsin Driver's License and sign a bill of sale. A Wisconsin Concealed Carry License is a plus. I can meet people in the Fennimore or Platteville areas.

title: Want To Buy:  Use caution when buying knives from a guy in Algonquin!! / Also looking for quality folders
postcontent:
Since discovering Armslist I have done a lot of business with some great people.  I am a rather broke special education teacher who really can not afford many nice things and Armslist has helped me find great deals that makes protecting myself and family affordable.  However, today I bought a Cold Steel blade from a seller in Algonquin.  This whole thing is my fault annd I just want to make sure people do not do what I did.  

I wanted to meet the guy in a public place to look at the two knives I was interested in in detail.  When he said that he didn't want to get out of his car I should have known something was wrong.  I looked at the blade in my car while the snow came down and it looked good.  When I got home I looked at it in better light and discovered that not only was the profile of the blade massively crooked(see attached picture), but the pocket clip was missing screwes.  At this point I figured I could pay to have it reprofiled and put one of the lefty screws on the right.  Well, as soon as I put the screw it, it fell out.  The hole was stripped.  I then looked at the other two lefty screws only to see that they were stripped.  I messaged the seller and asked if I could exchange this for other products since I didn't want to be a total jerk.  He explained to me that "buyer beware".  Now this is my fault.  But, please do not do what I did.  If you buy from this guy please take the time and look over every aspect of his blades; because he will not make it right.  Sure legally he has no obligation to help me; his customer.  However, he could have done the right thing morally and ethically.  So if you are looking at a blade from Algonquin, please double and triple check it before giving the guy money.

title: For Sale:  FN (Browning) Hi Power MK III with FNH logo
postcontent:
This is a 2002 FN HP MK III.  It is a full-blooded Browning Hi Power MK III with a different roll stamp on the slide, not a clone.  It has the Browning serial number format; but it actually has the FNH logo stamped on the side, and is the only one I've ever seen that had it.  Most read "Fabrique Nationale Herstal Belgique" on the slide.  Kind of unique, but by no means rare. They are still in production, but haven't been imported to the US for a few years.

It is in excellent shape.  The matte epoxy finish doesn't have the gloss of its Standard American counterpart, but it is extremely tough.  There is not a scratch on the exterior, except where the frame rails rub the dust cover, about 1/4" visible on each side.  The barrel and bore are still shiny.  The trigger breaks crisply without any noticeable creep.  Novak plain black sights have been installed, the pistol is otherwise unmodified.

I have a few full-frame 9mm pistols in the stable now, including an older Hi Power that I'm interested in restoring.  I'd like to add a 1911 to my collection, so is my motivation for offering this beautiful instrument to the market.  Original case included, along with cable lock,  plus the factory 13-round and Mec-Gar 10-round magazines with the "mousetrap" release spring.  Pachmayr grips installed, stock resin contour grips and Hogue Tulipwood smooth grips included, if the buyer desires.  

I will ship, my FFL to yours for a flat $35.  It is also your obligation to determine if this firearm and its magazines are legal in your state or municipality.  Payment by cash or US Postal Service Money Order, absolutely no exceptions.  Feel free to email with any questions about the gun or if you're unsure about the firearm shipping process.
